{|class=wikitable |- !width=15%| Date !width=15%| {{nowrap|Incident level}} !width=30%| Location !colspan=2| Type |- ! colspan="4" style="width:75%;"| Description ! Notes |- | 6 August 1945 | [[Nuclear warfare|Nuclear bombing]] | [[Hiroshima]] |colspan=2| Bomb flown in on airplane and dropped over urban area; 13kt explosion |- |colspan=4| {{main|Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki}}
[[United States of America]] aviators nuked Hiroshima. More than 70,000 fatalities were estimated. | |- | 9 August 1945 | Nuclear bombing | [[Nagasaki]] |colspan=2| Bomb flown in on airplane and dropped over urban area; 21kt explosion |- |colspan=4| {{main|Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki}}
[[United States of America]] aviators nuked Nagasaki. More than 39,000 fatalities were estimated. | |- | 5 December 1965 | [[Broken Arrow (nuclear)|Broken arrow]] | coast of Japan |colspan=2| Loss of a nuclear bomb |- |colspan=4| A US Navy aircraft with one [[B43 nuclear bomb]] fell off the [[aircraft carrier]] [[USS Ticonderoga (CV 14)|''Ticonderoga'']] into {{convert|16200|ft}} of water while the ship was underway from [[Vietnam]] to [[Yokosuka (city)|Yokosuka]], Japan. The weapon was never recovered. [[United States Navy|Navy]] documents show it happened about {{convert|80|mi}} from the [[Amami Islands]] and {{convert|200|mi}} from [[Okinawa]].<ref>{{cite news|author=CNN |title=Cold War: Broken Arrows (1960e) |url=http://www.cnn.com/SPECIALS/cold.war/experience/the.bomb/broken.arrows/content/1960e.html |publisher=CNN |year=1998 |accessdate=17 June 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070327211540/http://www.cnn.com/SPECIALS/cold.war/experience/the.bomb/broken.arrows/content/1960e.html |archivedate=27 March 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> | |- | March 1981 | [[International Nuclear Event Scale|INES]] Level 2 | [[Tsuruga]] |colspan=2| Overexposure of workers |- |colspan=4| More than 100 workers were exposed to doses of up to 155 millirem per day radiation during repairs of a nuclear power plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuclearfiles.org/menu/key-issues/nuclear-weapons/issues/accidents/accidents-1980's-01.htm |title=1980s accidents |publisher=Nuclearfiles.org |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> | |- | June 1999 | INES Level 2<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.climatesceptics.org/event/841 |title=Criticality accident during periodic inspection &#124; Nuclear power in Europe |publisher=Climatesceptics.org |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> | [[Shika Nuclear Power Plant|Shika plant]], [[Ishikawa Prefecture]] |colspan=2| Control rod malfunction |- |colspan=4| Operators attempting to insert one control rod accidentally withdrew three causing a 15-minute uncontrolled sustained reaction at the number 1 reactor of [[Shika Nuclear Power Plant]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/15/business/worldbusiness/15iht-nuke.4924774.html Japanese utility to shut reactor after admitting accident cover-up]</ref> | |- | 30 September 1999 | INES Level 4 | [[Ibaraki Prefecture]] |colspan=2| [[Criticality accident|Accidental criticality]] |- |colspan=4| {{main|Tokaimura nuclear accident|}} During preparation of a [[uranyl nitrate]] solution, uranium in solution exceeded the [[critical mass]], at a uranium reprocessing facility in [[Tokaimura|Tokai-mura]] northeast of Tokyo, Japan. Three workers were exposed to (neutron) radiation doses in excess of allowable limits. Two of these workers died. 116 other workers received lesser doses of 1 mSv or greater though not in excess of the allowable limit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/inf37.html |title=Tokaimura Criticality Accident |publisher=World-nuclear.org |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uic.com.au/nip52.htm |title=Tokaimura Criticality Accident Nuclear Issues Briefing Paper # 52 |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=3 March 2008 |accessdate=19 April 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303234104/http://www.uic.com.au/nip52.htm |archivedate=3 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isis-online.org/publications/tokai.html |title=Chronology and Press Reports of the Tokaimura Criticality |publisher=Isis-online.org |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/5165736.stm |title=Timeline: Nuclear plant accidents |publisher=BBC News |date=11 July 2006 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> | |- | 11–15 March 2011 | INES Level&nbsp;3{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} | [[Fukushima II Nuclear Power Plant]], [[Fukushima Prefecture]] |colspan=2| Earthquake/tsunami damage, overheating, possible radioactivity emergency |- |colspan=4| {{See also|Timeline of the Fukushima II nuclear accidents|Timeline of the Fukushima I nuclear accidents}} After the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami]] of 11 March, the [[Nuclear reactor technology|cooling systems]] for three reactors (numbers 1, 2 and 4) of the Fukushima II (Fukushima Dai-ni) nuclear power plant were compromised due to damage from the tsunami.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan Earthquake: NEI Updates for Saturday, March 12 |url=http://www.nei.org/newsandevents/information-on-the-japanese-earthquake-and-reactors-in-that-region/japan-earthquake-additional-nei-updates/japan-earthquake-nei-updates-for-saturday-march-12/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110324071827/http://www.nei.org/newsandevents/information-on-the-japanese-earthquake-and-reactors-in-that-region/japan-earthquake-additional-nei-updates/japan-earthquake-nei-updates-for-saturday-march-12/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=24 March 2011 |publisher=[[Nuclear Energy Institute]] |accessdate=2 April 2011 }}</ref> Nuclear Engineering International reported that all four units were successfully [[Scram|automatically shut down]], but emergency diesel generators at the site were out of order.<ref name=nei-20110311>{{Cite news|url=http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectioncode=132&storyCode=2059127 |title=Japan initiates emergency protocol after earthquake |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=11 March 2011 |accessdate=11 March 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314192321/http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectioncode=132&storyCode=2059127 |archivedate=14 March 2011 |df= }}</ref> People were evacuated around {{convert|10|km|mi}} from the plant, due to possible [[radioactive contamination]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Sumit Paul-Choudhury, Rowan Hooper|title=Japanese nuclear crisis spreads to two more plants|url=https://www.newscientist.com/blogs/shortsharpscience/2011/03/massive-explosion-rips-through.html|publisher=[[New Scientist]]|date=13 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Pete Norman |title=Japan: 200,000 Evacuated From Near Reactors |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Video-Nuclear-Power-Plant-Emergencies-After-Japan-Earthquake-And-Tsunami/Article/201103215950844?f=rss |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=13 March 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315131647/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Video-Nuclear-Power-Plant-Emergencies-After-Japan-Earthquake-And-Tsunami/Article/201103215950844?f=rss |archivedate=15 March 2011 |df= }}</ref> By 15 March, all four reactors at Daini were reported shutdown, cold and safe.<ref>IAEA, [http://www.iaea.org/newscenter/news/2011/fukushima150311.html Fukushima 2011 March 15 update] (accessed 20 March 2011)</ref> | |- | 11 March 2011 – onwards | INES Level&nbsp;7<ref>Ministry of Economy, Trade, and Industry of Japan/NISA: [http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110412-4.pdf INES (the International Nuclear and Radiological Event Scale) Rating on the Events in Fukushima Dai-ichi Nuclear Power Station by the Tohoku District – off the Pacific Ocean Earthquake] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/69MikbzsO?url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110412-4.pdf |date=23 July 2012 }} (12 April 2011)</ref> | [[Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant]], [[Fukushima Prefecture]] |colspan=2| Earthquake/tsunami damage, multiple meltdowns, core breaches, explosions, radiological releases, cooling failures |- |colspan=4| {{main|Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster}}
After the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami]] of 11 March, the [[Nuclear reactor technology|cooling systems]] for multiple reactors (units 1, 2, 3) and spent fuel cooling ponds (all 6 units and central pool) of the Fukushima I (Fukushima Dai-ichi) nuclear power plant were compromised due to damage from the tsunami. | |} [[File:Fukushima I by Digital Globe crop.jpg|thumb|The 2011 [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]], the worst [[nuclear accident]] in 25 years, displaced 50,000 households after [[radiation]] leaked into the air, soil and sea.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-26/fukushima-retiree-to-lead-anti-nuclear-motion.html |title=Fukushima Retiree Leads Anti-Nuclear Shareholders at Tepco Annual Meeting |author=Tomoko Yamazaki and Shunichi Ozasa |date=27 June 2011 |work=Bloomberg }}</ref>]]
